ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical components of photothermal materials play an important role in the generation of solar steam. Pomelo peel contains a significant amount of glucose which can be transformed into carbon dots by hydrothermal process [40]. These carbon dots often possess hydrophilic groups on their surface [36]. To investigate this aspect, XPS analysis was conducted to determine the surface chemical compositions of CPP, CDs-CPP, and CDs@CPP, as shown in Fig. 4 . The primary elements detected in all three materials were carbon and oxygen, and distinct differences in the high-resolution spectra of the C ls peak and O ls peak were observed (Fig. 4a). The varying heights of C 1s peak and O 1 s peak reflect the differing amounts of these elements present, indicative of the existence of various chemical groups in the samples that can significantly influence their properties. Moreover, the presence of CC (284.5
e V
), C–O (286.5
e V
), and CO (287.8
e V
) bonds was identified in all three samples (Fig. 4b). These bonds suggest the existence of some hydrophilic groups (e.g., COOH) that can enhance the wettability of resultant samples [38,41]. Improving the hydrophilicity of the material is also advantageous for water transportation and can thus enhance solar evaporation rate. However, the glucose will undergo thermal decomposition at high temperature (700 °C), leading to its decomposition and disappearance [42]. Therefore, the hydrophilic groups content in CPP and CDs-CPP maybe lower than that in CDs@CPP.

In contrast, CDs@CPP synthesized using our proposed one-step method did not exhibit the desired absorption ability seen in CPP and CDs-CPP. However, CDs@CPP did show significant absorption improvement across the wavelength range of simulated sunlight (200–1200
n m
) when compared to DPP. This indicates that the hydrothermal process employed in our one-step method plays a significant role in enhancing the light absorption capability of the material. While high light adsorption can enhance the efficiency of solar-thermal conversion and solar evaporation rate [38,44], it is important to note that such efficiency improvement is not solely determined by light adsorption. Rather, it is the result of various factors, such as material structure, wettability, and others, working in conjunction.
